item.title: NSW man charged after woman’s body found
item.description: A man has been charged with murder after the body of his 18-year-old girlfriend was found in the NSW town of Maitland.

item.title: Clashes ahead of Trump rally in Oklahoma
item.description: Supporters and detractors of US President Donald Trump continue to gather in Tulsa, Oklahoma where he is scheduled to take the stage for the first of his signature rallies during the coronavirus pandemic.

item.title: Victoria bucks trend, reimposes some curbs
item.description: Victoria has been forced to reimpose some COVID-19-related restrictions and defer others for three weeks after the state suffered its worst day of new cases in more than two months.

item.title: New Victoria COVID cases delay easing
item.description: Victoria will tighten coronavirus restrictions following another double-digit spike in cases and amid fears of a second wave.

item.title: China charges two Canadians with spying
item.description: Chinese prosecutors say they have charged two detained Canadians for suspected espionage, indictments that could result in life imprisonment, in a case that has driven a diplomatic wedge between Ottawa and Beijing.

item.title: Pompeo blasts China’s ‘coercion’ of Aust
item.description: US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo says he raised China's "coercion" of Australia during a frank, six-hour meeting with China's top diplomat in Hawaii.

item.title: Queries over Ann Marie Smith’s inheritance
item.description: Irregular spending of about $70,000 from a large inheritance left to South Australian neglect victim Ann Marie Smith has sparked further investigations.

item.title: NSW ‘gun supply group’ to apply for bail
item.description: Two alleged gun suppliers arrested in a counter-terrorism investigation will bide their time in custody before applying for bail in two weeks' time.

item.title: China denies being behind Aus cyber strike
item.description: Deputy Prime Minister Michael McCormack won't be drawn on who is behind the spate of cyber strikes on Australia, as China denied any part in the attacks, saying such suggestions are "baseless".

item.title: New Greens senator to pursue treaty
item.description: Aboriginal activist Lidia Thorpe will make getting a treaty off the ground one of her key aims when she enters federal parliament as a Greens senator.
